ously repressive and creative power of military "fencelines," sites of symbolic negotiation and struggle involving gender, race, and class that divide the social landscape in communities that host US bases.Intimacy Across the Fencelines anchors the global US military complex and US-Japan security alliance in intimate everyday experiences and emotions, illuminating important aspects of the lived experiences of war and imperialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aIntercountry marriagezJapanzOkinawa-ken. 0aInterracial marriagezJapanzOkinawa-ken. 0aMilitary bases, AmericanxSocial aspectszJapanzOkinawa-ken. 0aSoldiersxSexual behaviorzJapanzOkinawa-ken. 0aSoldiersxSexual behaviorzUnited States. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  aOkinawa, Japan, fencelines, US Foreign Policy, militarism, US Military.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501750427zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501750427423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501750427/original  a978-3-11-069046-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070473-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_CL_HIC